Content: Libra white paper shows that the dollar is not one to one, and the reserve also invests in low interest-rate safety assets and forms a basket of currencies in many countries. Libra will move toward a separate unit of currency, reminiscent of Keynes's Bancor. It is simply surprising if the global financial power does not block the project.

Content: Is it possible that facebook's Libra is the edict of milan that authorized christianity? It's been a long time since skeptics who criticize the volatility of bitcoin predicted the era of stable coin. from the Bretton Woods system perspective, the dollar-fixed stable coin is much stronger than the regime-destructive property. It is also a global company, not a bank with a derivative currency license. It is more to watch than to cheer.

Author: designer#4893
Content:
the real problem with Libra is that the first concept of fixing prices will be shaken by global villagers who want to keep them as inflation targets for their currencies without exchanging money. making fine adjustments to keep this promise will strangely make the organization resemble the government.

Again, the Financial Times published a column in which the Libra is lit at the speed of light. the logic is interesting. they say it is difficult to help unbank people living in Africa, the Amazon, and the Philippines because they have to maintain offices that exchange Libra with real money. at first glance, it is convincing, but it shows that you don't understand the mess that's happening at all. bitcoin or blockchain is a trust game. when trust is secured, it becomes a value without exchanging money. bitcoin doesn't even exchange money.
